“Y2Q”

If you haven’t heard this phrase yet, chances are you will soon. 

Y2Q is what convinced me to trade in my Fort Lauderdale, FL beach shoes for Ottawa, Canada snowshoes and join Quantropi.

Y2Q is important to understand if you use the internet for any type of financial, legal, or sensitive exchange of information including online shopping, online banking, applying for a mortgage or insurance, “DocuSigning” anything, and even email.

Y2Q is important to understand if you have any kind of smart Internet of Things (IoT) device like a Ring doorbell, Nest thermostat, security camera, baby monitor, fitness watch, or any device you can access or control from a mobile device through the internet.

Put simply, every day we rely on devices that are embedded with sensors, software, or other technologies that collect and securely transmit our data. To keep our personal information safe, the data is “encrypted.” But how safe is it, really? This is where Y2Q comes in.

Y2Q stands for “Years to Quantum” and it represents the date when a commercially viable quantum computer becomes available that is powerful enough to break our current encryption standards. Instead of the binary 1’s and 0’s used by today’s classic computers, quantum computers store data and solve problems using the properties of quantum physics – making them much faster and more efficient than supercomputers for certain applications (like breaking encryption).

Estimates as to when Y2Q will occur vary from as long as a decade to as short as just a couple years. If this makes you feel better, it probably shouldn’t. Technology and innovation have a habit of advancing much faster than people expect (just think about ChatGPT). In the case of quantum, technology companies are spending over $30B per year in an arms race to create more and more powerful quantum computers. 

And for good reason – quantum computing has enormous potential to solve a wide range of problems in today’s society. But as history has repeatedly shown, revolutionary new technology can have unintended uses and consequences – and in this case, that means the end of the classical encryption that has secured our world for decades. In other words, the $50 trillion dollars of transactions in today’s digital economy and a wide range of other sensitive online transactions will no longer be private or secure.

Ultimately you should form your own opinion as to when Y2Q will occur, but in my view “sooner” seems more likely than “later”. In my next post, I’ll summarize some eye-opening events from the last 45 days that could rapidly advance the Y2Q timeframe.

In the meantime, to learn more about what is being done to keep information private and secure, follow Quantropi Inc. – a leading provider of quantum secure encryption to safeguard our digital world “today, tomorrow…forever.”

WORLD RECORD IN FACTORIZATION WITH NON-HYBRID QUANTUM ALGORITHM

We are proud to announce that Kipu Quantum has achieved a world record in factorization with a purely quantum algorithm, meaning no classical optimization was performed. We have factorized a 48-bit integer in 10 qubits of ion-trap Quantinuum's quantum processor with our innovative non-hybrid quantum computing paradigm: Digitized-Counterdiabatic Quantum Factorization (DCQF).

We have also internal results, tested in trapped-ion and superconducting quantum computers, with even further records using hybrid DCQF, outperforming by far the announcement today. We will keep disclosing them along the next weeks and months, after suitable IP strategy, smart productizing, and customer deals.

Anyone's ambitious goals should include, evidently, a scalable approach towards solving RSA-64 and RSA-128 with digital quantum computing methods. We are tackling such challenges with our purely-quantum and hybrid DCQF paradigms. However, we are also considering a scalable path towards larger integers, including RSA-2048, which may need digital-analog quantum computing (DAQC) encoding.

Kipu Quantum is a unique world-leading company with the most creative technology and talented management teams, which invents, owns, and develops the expertise for productizing DCQC, DCQO, DCQF, DAQC, and many other revolutionary quantum computing paradigms, bringing quantum advantage for industry use cases to the present of our NISQ era.

At Kipu Quantum, each investment effort, in your preferred currency, produces breakthroughs in quantum technology, products, and business.

Stay tuned for periodic announcements of our quantum computing records and further news on finance, chemistry, optimization, logistics, factorization, among others. Kipu Quantum develops unique and proprietary hardware-dependent application-specific quantum solutions with most competitive results.

Quantum destiny is all.

Happy International Women’s Day! Today, we celebrate the incredible achievements of women throughout history. We are proud to highlight and honour 𝗠𝗮𝗿𝘆 𝗖𝗮𝗿𝘁𝘄𝗿𝗶𝗴𝗵𝘁 through this special digital portrait by Eric Chan.

𝗪𝗵𝗮𝘁 𝗶𝘀 𝘀𝗵𝗲 𝗯𝗲𝘀𝘁 𝗸𝗻𝗼𝘄𝗻 𝗳𝗼𝗿?Mary Cartwright was a British mathematician who was one of the pioneers in what would later be known as chaos theory – a relatively new branch of mathematics that deals with surprises, the unpredictability of events and the nonlinearity of life.

𝗪𝗵𝗮𝘁 𝗱𝗶𝗱 𝘀𝗵𝗲 𝘄𝗶𝗻?Cartwright has won numerous awards including being the first woman recipient of the prestigious De Morgan Medal, the highest award of the London Mathematical Society.
